result.execSummary:
All charges against Tuhkeyo B Troop in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Tuhkeyo B Troop is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

01:02 PM Defendant Tuhkeyo B Troop in court.  Andrew Nesheim appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

The Court calls the matter for Status of Counsel.
Defendant is not eligible for State Public Defender representation.
Defendant requests the court appoint counsel.  Court swears defendant.
The Court conducts a colloquy with the Defendant.   
The Court finds that the Defendant should qualify for SPD representation based on what was listed on the Petition for Court Appointed Counsel paperwork.
The Court orders the Defendant to recall SPD.

The Court recesses at 01:08 PM for the Defendant to call SPD.
The Court recalls the matter at 02:20 PM with the same appearances.

The Defendant clarifies the weekly rate and that is why he didn't qualify for SPD.
Court grants request for court appointed counsel, repayment at the rate of $75.00 per month commencing March 15, 2022.

The Court finds good cause to toll the time limits for a prelim hearing.
The Court will take the prelim hearing scheduled on 02/16/2022 at 09:15 AM off the calendar and orders the State to call its witnesses off.
